            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Richmond</placeName>
                <date>19 July/36</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. Mr Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">My dear friend</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Some months past I was called upon<lb/> by the <persName>Revd. Mr
                        A<add>?</add></persName> who asked me if the 9c of the 2c of
                    <persName>Job</persName><lb/> was correctly rendered “curse God and die” after
                examining<lb/> the Hebrew text I told him my impression was that<lb/> it should be
                “Bless God and die” how then he asked<lb/> are we to account for the words in the
                English Bible<lb/> I replied by the seventy translators regulating the points<lb/>
                which have caused them to <add>?</add> gross <add>?</add> upon<lb/> many texts. That
                without the several points we could<lb/> not understand the true meaning of
                scripture, and<lb/> that by means of the amounts we are made to<lb/> understand the
                subject matter, I maintain<add>?</add> my position<lb/> by the following examples.
                The words in <persName>Job</persName> are<lb/>
                <add>Hebrew</add> we read in 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> Gens 22<add>?</add> “and God
                blessed”<lb/> using the letters and points <add>Hebrew</add> and in the 145 psalm
                    <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> “bless the Lord” and in other places <add>Hebrew</add>
                numbers 22<add>?</add>
                <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> the letters &amp; points the same that is used in
                    <persName>Job</persName> 2c. 9c. the word<lb/> to curse in the 22c. 6 of numbers
                is <add>Hebrew</add> and in <add>?</add>.28c<lb/> 16 to 19<add>?</add> to curse is
                    <add>Hebrew</add> and the last word in the last verse<lb/> of the last chapter
                of <add>?</add> to curse is <add>Hebrew</add> those were<lb/> all the authorities I
                could find applicable to the subject<lb/> having no one in this congregation in
                whose knowledge<lb/> I can confide. I without hesitation apply to you at<lb/> your
                leisure forward me with your opinion discarding<lb/> all speculation as to the
                motives of <persName>Jobs</persName> wife—wishing<lb/> you all happiness, I remain
                your friend</p>
            <p>Jacob Mordecai</p>
            <p>ask <persName>Mrs Hart</persName> if she succeeded<lb/> in getting <add>?</add>
                work</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>To</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The <addressee>Revd Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
